    {
      "num": 1,
      "text": "In a skimming scheme, which characteristic most distinguishes it from a cash larceny scheme?",
      "tag": "Asset Misappropriation - Cash Receipts",
      "options": [
        "B. Skimming requires collusion with external vendors",
        "C. Cash larceny involves stealing inventory instead of cash",
        "D. Cash larceny occurs before bank reconciliation",
        "A. Skimming occurs before cash is recorded in the accounting system"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "Per CFE Manual 2024, skimming is the theft of cash before it enters the accounting system, making detection more difficult as no audit trail exists. This timing distinction is fundamental to classification and detection methodologies for cash receipt schemes.",
      "justification_wrong": "Cash larceny occurs after cash is recorded in the books, creating reconciliation discrepancies. Skimming does not inherently require vendor collusion, and cash larceny specifically involves cash theft, not inventory. The recording timing is the critical differentiator per ACFE standards.",
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "financial_transactions/quiz_001_en.json"
    },
    {
      "num": 2,
      "text": "In a skimming scheme involving unrecorded sales, which analytical procedure would be MOST effective in detecting the fraud when inventory records are maintained accurately?",
      "tag": "Asset Misappropriation - Skimming",
      "options": [
        "C. Analyzing accounts receivable aging reports for unusual patterns",
        "D. Testing internal controls over cash receipt procedures",
        "A. Comparing cost of goods sold to sales ratio with industry benchmarks and prior periods",
        "B. Performing a horizontal analysis of sales revenue over multiple periods"
      ],
      "correct": 2,
      "justification_correct": "Per CFE Manual, when sales are skimmed but inventory is properly recorded, the cost-of-goods-sold-to-sales ratio becomes abnormally high compared to benchmarks. This occurs because recorded COGS reflects actual inventory sold, while sales are understated, creating a disproportionate ratio that signals potential skimming of unrecorded sales transactions.",
      "justification_wrong": "Horizontal analysis may show declining sales but cannot differentiate skimming from legitimate business decline. Receivables aging is irrelevant for cash sales skimming. Control testing may identify weaknesses but won't detect fraud already occurring. The ratio analysis provides quantitative evidence of the specific skimming pattern.",
      "difficulty": "HARD",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "financial_transactions/quiz_001_en.json"
    },
    {
      "num": 3,
      "text": "In a skimming scheme involving lapping, which internal control deficiency is MOST critical to the perpetrator's ability to sustain the fraud over multiple accounting periods?",
      "tag": "Asset Misappropriation - Skimming",
      "options": [
        "C. Inadequate physical security over cash storage facilities",
