    {
      "num": 5,
      "text": "An employee retains a sales amount in cash without recording it in the system. According to the CFE Examiners Manual, what is this type of fraud called?",
      "tag": "Skimming",
      "options": [
        "A. Skimming",
        "B. Cash larceny",
        "C. Lapping",
        "D. Kiting"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "Skimming involves the theft of resources before they are recorded in the accounting system, leaving no direct audit trail of the diverted transaction. (CFE Fraud Examiners Manual 2024)",
      "justification_wrong": "Cash larceny occurs after recording; lapping is a scheme to cover up deviations in accounts receivable; kiting involves manipulation of checks between bank accounts.",
      "difficulty": "EASY",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "financial_transactions/quiz_006_en.json"
    },
    {
      "num": 6,
      "text": "Sandra, a receptionist at a dental practice, collects patient copayments in cash at the time of service. The practice does not issue receipts unless patients specifically request them. Sandra has been removing cash payments from patients whose accounts she knows are paid primarily through insurance reimbursements rather than subsequent billing statements. She records these transactions in the appointment system as \"insurance pending\" rather than \"copay collected.\" Which characteristic of the practice's operations is Sandra primarily exploiting to conceal her skimming scheme?",
      "tag": "Skimming",
      "options": [
        "A. The absence of independent verification between cash collected and transactions recorded in the accounting system",
        "B. The failure to implement adequate background checks during the hiring process for cash-handling employees",
        "C. The lack of surveillance cameras positioned to monitor the reception area where payments are collected",
        "D. The practice's decision to accept cash payments rather than requiring all payments by credit card or check"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "justification_correct": "Sandra is exploiting the lack of independent reconciliation between cash received and amounts recorded. Skimming occurs before funds enter the accounting system, making it difficult to detect without controls that verify all payments collected are properly recorded. The primary weakness is that no one independently verifies that the cash Sandra collects matches what she enters into the system. She can simply pocket cash and not record it (or record it as pending), and without reconciliation between actual receipts and recorded transactions, the theft remains hidden. This represents a fundamental internal control deficiency in cash receipts handling.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option B is incorrect because while background checks are a preventive detective control, they do not address the operational weakness Sandra is actively exploiting to conceal her ongoing theft. Even employees with clean backgrounds can commit fraud when internal controls are absent. Option C is incorrect because surveillance cameras are a detective control that might identify suspicious behavior, but Sandra is specifically exploiting the recordkeeping gap that allows unrecorded cash to go unnoticed; cameras alone would not detect transactions that are never recorded. Option D is incorrect because accepting cash is not itself a control weakness that Sandra exploits; skimming can occur with checks and other payment forms through similar lack of reconciliation. The payment method is less relevant than the absence of verification controls."
    },
    {
      "num": 7,
      "text": "Miranda, a cashier at a retail pharmacy, has been stealing cash from the register by voiding legitimate customer transactions after customers leave the store and pocketing the cash from those sales. To detect this scheme, which of the following would be the MOST effective control?",
      "tag": "Cash Larceny",
      "options": [
        "A. Implementing a system that requires manager approval for all transaction voids and refunds with real-time notification",
        "B. Conducting surprise cash counts at the end of each shift and comparing totals to register tape summaries",
        "C. Requiring two employees to be present at all times when the register is open for business operations",
        "D. Reconciling daily bank deposit amounts to the total sales recorded in the point-of-sale system"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "justification_correct": "Requiring manager approval for voids with real-time notification is the most effective control because it directly addresses the mechanism of the fraud. Cash larceny schemes involving post-transaction voids exploit the ability to alter records after the sale is complete. By requiring immediate supervisory approval and notification for each void, the scheme becomes difficult to execute without detection. The real-time aspect prevents Miranda from accumulating numerous fraudulent voids, and the manager review creates accountability and scrutiny over the specific transactions being manipulated. This control prevents the fraud at the point of occurrence rather than detecting it after the fact.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option B (surprise cash counts) may eventually detect shortages but is less effective because in this void scheme, the register will likely balance since Miranda voids the transaction and removes the corresponding cash—there is no register shortage to find. Option C (two employees present) provides general deterrence but does not prevent the scheme since voids can still be processed with another employee nearby who may not be monitoring every transaction detail. Option D (reconciling deposits to sales) will not detect this scheme because the voided transactions reduce recorded sales to match the deposited amount—the books will appear to balance since both the sale record and the cash are removed from the system."
    },
    {
      "num": 8,
      "text": "Maria, an accounts receivable clerk at a wholesale distribution company, has been stealing customer payments for six months. When Customer A sends a check for $2,000, Maria pockets it and does not record the payment. Two weeks later, when Customer B sends a check for $2,500, Maria applies $2,000 of it to Customer A's account and steals the remaining $500. She continues this pattern with subsequent payments. Which control would be most effective in detecting Maria's scheme?",
      "tag": "Lapping",
      "options": [
        "A. Having an independent party prepare monthly reconciliations of customer statements to the accounts receivable subsidiary ledger and investigating customer disputes about account balances",
        "B. Requiring Maria to take mandatory consecutive vacation days while another employee performs her duties and processes incoming payments during her absence",
        "C. Implementing a policy that requires all customer payments above $1,000 to be approved by a supervisor before being posted to the accounts receivable system",
        "D. Segregating duties so that Maria can receive customer payments but cannot make adjustments or write-offs to customer accounts without managerial approval"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "justification_correct": "Mandatory vacation is the most effective detective control for lapping schemes because lapping requires continuous concealment through ongoing manipulation of payments. The perpetrator must constantly apply new receipts to cover previous thefts. When Maria is absent and another employee handles payment processing, the scheme will collapse because incoming payments will not be misapplied to cover the older stolen amounts, causing customer account discrepancies to surface immediately. This temporary separation exposes the cascading effect of the fraud that has been hidden through continuous activity.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option A, while helpful, may not detect lapping promptly because Maria can manipulate the timing of postings to ensure that account balances appear current when statements are sent, and customers may not dispute their accounts if payments are eventually credited (albeit late). Option C is ineffective because supervisor approval of payment posting does not prevent or detect the misapplication of funds; Maria would simply show the legitimate payment amount being posted, just to the wrong customer account. Option D addresses a different fraud risk (unauthorized adjustments or write-offs) but does not prevent lapping, since Maria only needs the ability to receive and misapply payments between customer accounts, which she retains under this control."
    },
    {
      "num": 9,
      "text": "Rebecca, the accounts receivable manager at Stratton Industries, has sole responsibility for opening mail, posting customer payments to accounts, and preparing bank deposits. Management suspects a lapping scheme may be occurring. Which of the following controls would be MOST effective in preventing lapping in this scenario?",
      "tag": "Lapping Prevention",
      "options": [
        "A. Require segregation of duties so that mail opening and cash handling are performed by different employees than those who post payments to customer accounts.",
        "B. Implement a policy requiring Rebecca to take consecutive vacation days annually during which another employee performs her duties.",
        "C. Conduct periodic unannounced reconciliations comparing customer account statements to the accounts receivable subsidiary ledger.",
        "D. Establish mandatory dual authorization for all write-offs of customer accounts exceeding a predetermined threshold amount."
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "justification_correct": "Segregation of duties is the most effective preventive control against lapping schemes. Lapping occurs when an employee with access to both incoming cash receipts and account posting steals a payment from one customer and conceals it by applying a subsequent payment from another customer to the first customer's account. By separating the functions of cash handling and accounts receivable posting between different employees, the opportunity to perpetrate a lapping scheme is eliminated at its source. This control prevents the fraud from occurring rather than merely detecting it after the fact, making it the strongest preventive measure.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option B (mandatory vacation) is a detective control rather than a preventive control. While it may help uncover an ongoing lapping scheme when another employee temporarily assumes the duties and notices irregularities, it does not prevent the scheme from being initiated or continuing after the employee returns. Option C (periodic reconciliations) is also a detective control that may identify discrepancies caused by lapping but does not prevent the employee from executing the scheme in the first place. Option D (dual authorization for write-offs) addresses a different fraud risk related to fictitious write-offs or unauthorized account adjustments, but does not prevent lapping, which involves the misapplication of actual customer payments rather than account write-offs."
    },
    {
      "num": 10,
      "text": "Maria, a retail cashier, accepts $150 cash from a customer for merchandise. She enters the transaction into the point-of-sale system but immediately voids it, removing the system record. She pockets the $150 and gives the customer a receipt showing the voided transaction. Later that day, Tom, another cashier, removes $150 from his register drawer after properly recording a cash sale and places it in his pocket. What types of schemes have Maria and Tom committed?",
      "tag": "Skimming vs Larceny",
      "options": [
        "A. Maria committed skimming and Tom committed cash larceny",
        "B. Maria committed cash larceny and Tom committed skimming",
        "C. Both Maria and Tom committed skimming schemes",
        "D. Both Maria and Tom committed cash larceny schemes"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "justification_correct": "Maria committed skimming because she took the cash before it was recorded in the company's accounting system. Although she entered the transaction initially, she voided it, ensuring the cash was never reflected in the company's books and records. Skimming involves the theft of cash before it enters the accounting system. Tom committed cash larceny because he stole money that had already been properly recorded as revenue in the point-of-sale system. Cash larceny involves stealing money after it has been recorded in the company's books, which creates a direct shortage that must be concealed through other means.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option B reverses the schemes—Maria's voiding of the transaction means the cash never entered the books (skimming), not larceny, while Tom's theft occurred after recording (larceny), not before. Option C incorrectly classifies Tom's theft as skimming when he stole recorded funds, which is the defining characteristic of larceny rather than skimming. Option D incorrectly classifies Maria's theft as larceny when she prevented the cash from being recorded by voiding the transaction, which is the hallmark of a skimming scheme rather than larceny."
    },
    {
      "num": 11,
      "text": "Karen, a cashier at a retail pharmacy, processes cash sales transactions but occasionally does not ring certain sales through the point-of-sale system. Instead, she pockets the cash from these unrecorded sales while providing customers with handwritten receipts that she claims are generated during system maintenance. Management suspects fraud and asks a Certified Fraud Examiner to identify the most effective data analytics procedure to detect this scheme. Which procedure would most likely reveal Karen's skimming activity?",
      "tag": "Skimming",
      "options": [
        "A. Compare inventory depletion records to recorded sales revenue to identify merchandise shortages that correspond to unrecorded revenue",
        "B. Reconcile daily cash register tapes to bank deposit slips to detect differences between receipts recorded and amounts deposited",
        "C. Analyze customer refund transactions for unusual patterns such as refunds processed without corresponding original sales",
        "D. Review employee timecard records against cash handling shifts to identify scheduling irregularities during high-volume periods"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "justification_correct": "Comparing inventory depletion to recorded sales is the most effective detection method for sales skimming schemes. When a cashier skims cash by not recording sales, the merchandise still leaves inventory, creating a discrepancy between physical inventory reduction and recorded revenue. This inventory shrinkage without corresponding sales revenue is a primary indicator of skimming at the point of sale. Since Karen is providing products to customers but not recording the transactions, inventory will show unexplained shortages that exceed normal shrinkage rates, making this analytical procedure the strongest detection tool for this specific scheme.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option B is incorrect because reconciling register tapes to deposits detects cash larceny (theft after recording), not skimming. In Karen's scheme, the sales are never recorded in the register, so the register tape and deposits would reconcile properly—both would simply be understated. Option C is incorrect because analyzing refund patterns detects fraudulent refund schemes, not skimming of unrecorded sales. Karen is not processing false refunds; she is simply not recording legitimate sales. Option D is incorrect because reviewing timecard and scheduling records does not directly detect skimming. While such analysis might identify opportunity, it does not reveal the actual inventory-to-sales discrepancy that evidences unrecorded transactions, making it a weaker detection method than inventory reconciliation."
    },
    {
      "num": 12,
      "text": "Marcus, a mail room clerk at a medical billing company, has been stealing customer payments that arrive as checks made payable to the company. He opens the envelopes, removes the checks, forges the company's endorsement, and deposits them into his personal bank account using a mobile banking app. The company's accounting system shows these invoices as outstanding. Which of the following fraud schemes is Marcus committing?",
      "tag": "Cash Larceny",
      "options": [
        "A. Cash larceny because he is stealing recorded payments after they have entered the accounting system",
        "B. Skimming because he is removing payments before they are recorded in the company's books",
        "C. Lapping because he is concealing the theft by applying subsequent payments to prior accounts",
        "D. Check tampering because he is altering the payee information on customer checks"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "justification_correct": "This is skimming, not cash larceny. Skimming occurs when an employee steals cash or checks before they are recorded in the company's accounting system. Since Marcus intercepts the checks in the mail room before they reach the accounting department, and the invoices remain outstanding in the system, the payments were never recorded. The key distinction is the timing of the theft relative to the recording of the transaction. Even though checks were stolen (which some might associate with cash larceny), the critical factor is that these receipts never entered the books.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option A is incorrect because cash larceny specifically involves stealing money that has already been recorded in the company's accounting records. In this scenario, the invoices remain outstanding, indicating the payments were never recorded. Option C is incorrect because lapping is a concealment technique where an employee covers a theft by applying a subsequent customer payment to a prior customer's account, creating a rolling scheme. Marcus is not using subsequent payments to conceal his theft. Option D is incorrect because check tampering involves altering a check that the organization has prepared (typically payable checks), such as changing the payee or amount. Marcus is not altering the checks themselves; he is simply stealing incoming checks and forging an endorsement."
    },
    {
      "num": 13,
      "text": "Margaret, an accounts receivable clerk at a regional medical supply distributor, has been stealing customer payments for eight months. She conceals the theft by applying subsequent payments from other customers to the accounts from which she stole. The company's external auditor is planning to send account balance confirmations to a sample of customers. Which of the following actions would be MOST effective for Margaret to prevent detection of her scheme through the confirmation process?",
      "tag": "Lapping",
      "options": [
        "A. Intercept confirmation responses from customers whose payments she diverted and alter the responses to match the company's understated records before returning them to the auditor",
        "B. Request that the auditor exclude from the confirmation sample any customers whose accounts show collection periods exceeding 90 days to avoid customer confusion",
        "C. Create fictitious credit memos to write off the outstanding balances of customers whose payments she stole prior to the confirmation date",
        "D. Delay recording recent legitimate payments in the accounting system until after confirmations are mailed so she has additional payments available to continue lapping"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "justification_correct": "Intercepting and altering confirmation responses is the most effective method to prevent detection because lapping creates a discrepancy between the company's records (which show inflated receivable balances) and customers' records (which show correct lower balances or zero balances if they paid). When customers receive confirmations showing they owe more than they actually do, they will disagree with the balance. By intercepting these responses and altering them to match the fraudulent records before they reach the auditor, Margaret eliminates the primary detection mechanism. This directly addresses the core vulnerability that external confirmations create for lapping schemes—independent third-party verification that bypasses the perpetrator's control over internal records.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option B is wrong because Margaret lacks authority to dictate which accounts auditors select for confirmation; auditors maintain independence in sample selection, and requesting exclusions would likely raise suspicion rather than prevent detection. Option C is wrong because creating fictitious credit memos might temporarily remove some balances from the books, but this creates a different fraud trail that requires additional approvals, generates documentation inconsistencies, and fails to address the systematic pattern of inflated balances across multiple lapped accounts that confirmations would reveal. Option D is wrong because delaying the recording of legitimate payments does not solve the fundamental problem—customers whose payments were stolen will still receive confirmations showing balances they already paid, and these customers will respond to the auditor indicating the discrepancy, thereby exposing the lapping scheme regardless of whether Margaret has additional payments to continue the rotation."
    },
    {
      "num": 14,
      "text": "Susan Martinez, the fraud examiner at Greenfield Medical Center, recently discovered that a billing clerk had been misappropriating patient payments by crediting incoming checks to other patient accounts with outstanding balances, then covering those accounts when subsequent payments arrived. Which of the following controls would be MOST effective in preventing this type of lapping scheme from occurring in the future?",
      "tag": "Lapping Prevention",
      "options": [
        "A. Requiring customers to receive monthly statements showing all payments credited to their accounts",
        "B. Implementing a policy that the billing clerk must take annual leave of at least five consecutive days",
        "C. Installing video surveillance cameras in the area where payment processing occurs",
        "D. Requiring the billing clerk to provide a fidelity bond before handling customer payments"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "justification_correct": "Sending monthly statements directly to customers is the most effective preventive control against lapping because it creates independent verification outside the perpetrator's control. When customers receive statements showing payments credited to their accounts, any discrepancies between what they paid and what was credited become immediately apparent. This external feedback loop makes lapping schemes extremely difficult to sustain, as the perpetrator cannot manipulate both the internal records and the customer's independent knowledge of their payments. The direct communication between the organization and the customer bypasses the fraudster's ability to conceal the misappropriation.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option B (mandatory vacation) is a detective control rather than a preventive one; it helps discover ongoing lapping schemes when the perpetrator is absent and cannot continue the cover-up cycle, but it does not prevent the scheme from starting. Option C (video surveillance) might deter some fraud but would not effectively prevent lapping since the fraudulent activity involves accounting entries rather than physical theft that cameras would capture; the clerk's legitimate job duties include processing payments. Option D (fidelity bond) is a compensatory control that provides insurance recovery after a loss occurs but does nothing to prevent the lapping scheme itself; bonds transfer risk but do not reduce the opportunity for fraud."
    },
    {
      "num": 15,
      "text": "During a routine audit at a retail pharmacy, the fraud examiner discovers that a cashier has been accepting customer payments for prescriptions but not recording certain transactions in the point-of-sale system. The cashier pockets the cash before it enters the pharmacy's accounting records. In a separate instance at the same pharmacy, another employee removes cash from the register drawer at the end of her shift after all sales have been properly recorded. How should the fraud examiner classify these two schemes?",
      "tag": "Skimming vs Larceny",
      "options": [
        "A. The first scheme is skimming because the cash was stolen before being recorded, while the second scheme is cash larceny because the theft occurred after the sales were recorded",
        "B. Both schemes are classified as skimming because both involve the theft of cash receipts by employees with access to customer payments",
        "C. The first scheme is cash larceny because it involves register manipulation, while the second scheme is skimming because it occurs after business hours",
        "D. Both schemes are classified as cash larceny because the stolen funds belonged to the employer at the time of the theft"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "justification_correct": "The key distinction between skimming and cash larceny is the point at which the theft occurs in relation to the accounting records. Skimming involves the theft of cash before it is recorded in the organization's books and records, making it an off-book scheme that is harder to detect through reconciliation. Cash larceny involves the theft of cash after it has been recorded in the accounting system, creating an on-book shortage that can be detected through reconciliation of physical cash to recorded amounts. In the first instance, the cashier steals payments before they enter the accounting system, which is skimming. In the second instance, the employee steals cash that has already been recorded, which is cash larceny.",
      "justification_wrong": "Option B incorrectly classifies both schemes as skimming, failing to recognize that the second scheme involves theft after recordation, which is the defining characteristic of cash larceny. Option C reverses the correct classifications and introduces irrelevant factors such as 'register manipulation' and timing of 'after business hours,' neither of which determines the distinction between skimming and larceny. Option D incorrectly classifies both as cash larceny and uses faulty reasoning about ownership; while both amounts belong to the employer, the critical factor is whether the theft occurred before or after accounting recordation, not ownership at the time of theft."
    },
